"Essential code requirements for the experiment:\n\n- Data loading and preparation\n  - Load MovieLens100K u.data from the current working directory with tab delimiter; expect columns: user_id, item_id, rating, timestamp; convert to binary implicit interactions (interaction = 1 if rating exists).\n  - Ensure user and item IDs map to contiguous integer indices for modeling.\n  - Implement a per-run train/test split using a leave-one-out strategy: for every user with at least 2 interactions, reserve exactly 1 random interaction as the test item and use the rest as training data.\n  - Ensure the split is reproducible via a seed (seed differs per run).\n\n- Model and training\n  - Use LensKit's ImplicitMF algorithm; expose key hyperparameters (n_factors, n_epochs, learning_rate, regularization) and keep them identical across runs except for the seed.\n  - Train on the train set for each run; ensure deterministic behavior given the seed.\n  - Maintain a fixed random seed usage for any internal randomness (e.g., initialization) so different runs with different seeds yield different results but are reproducible.\n\n- Seeds and experimental runs\n  - Execute the experiment for a configurable list of seeds (e.g., [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]); all other settings identical across runs.\n  - If a run fails, report and continue with remaining runs; do not abort the full experiment.\n\n- Evaluation protocol and metrics\n  - For each run, compute top-N recommendations for each user in the test set (N in {10, 20}).\n  - Compute per-user NDCG@N and Recall@N (binary relevance: test item present in top-N counts as relevant).\n  - Aggregate across users to obtain per-run mean NDCG@N and Recall@N.\n  - Aggregate across runs to obtain overall mean and standard deviation; report 95% confidence intervals if possible.\n\n- Output and logging\n  - Save per-run metrics to a structured CSV (e.g., results_runs.csv) with columns: run_id, seed, ndcg@10, recall@10, ndcg@20, recall@20, train_size, test_size, elapsed_seconds.\n  - Save an overall summary (mean, std, CI) to a separate CSV or a printed table.\n  - Print basic sanity checks (e.g., number of users with test items, average train interactions).\n\n- Reproducibility and provenance\n  - Record hyperparameter settings, dataset identifier/version, software/library versions (LensKit version, Python version) and the exact seeds used.\n  - Ensure the code prints or stores a reproducibility report header.\n\n- Resource constraints and robustness\n  - Enforce a reasonable time/memory budget per run; catch and log timeouts or memory errors; continue with remaining runs.\n\n- Compatibility and integration\n  - Code should rely only on LensKit APIs; not require external data transformations beyond the described splitting and metric computation steps.\n  - Provide clear entry points for configuration (seeds list, k-values, hyperparameters) and an instruction snippet to run the experiment."